@Eric Hougland As a KSU alumnus, I couldn't agree more. I was 2 when it happened, and went on to get an undergraduate degree from Kent in 1990. To their credit, despite being in a depressingly increasingly red state, the University does a good job at educating the students about it.

The dad of one of my college friends was an anthropology professor and was there during the shootings in 1970. He spoke about it often and I appreciated his insights. It had a profoundly traumatic impact on him unfortunately.

Trump's focus on dismantling institutions of higher learning (I am now a professor at Northeastern University) is dangerous, depressing, and has long-term implications. Sadly, it is not hard to imagine something like Kent State happening again.

